SIMPLE: neither
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Neither
<hw>Nei"ther</hw> <pr>(n⟦emac⟧"⟦th⟧⟦etil⟧r <it>or</it>
n⟦imac⟧"⟦th⟧⟦etil⟧r; 277)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>neither</ets>, <ets>nother</ets>, <ets>nouther</ets>, AS.
<ets>n⟦amac⟧w⟦edh⟧er</ets>, <ets>n⟦amac⟧hwae⟦edh⟧er</ets>;
<ets>n⟦amac⟧</ets> never, not + <ets>hwae⟦edh⟧er</ets> whether. The word
has followed the form of <ets>either</ets>. See <er>No</er>, and
<er>Whether</er>, and cf. <er>Neuter</er>, <er>Nor</er>.]</ety> <def>Not
either; not the one or the other.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Which of them shall I take?⟦br⟧
Both? one? or <qex>neither</qex>? <qex>Neither</qex> can be enjoyed,⟦br⟧
If both remain alive.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>neither</qex> loves,⟦br⟧
Nor either cares for him.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Neither</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Neither
<hw>Nei"ther</hw>, <pos>conj.</pos> <def>Not either; generally used to
introduce the first of two or more coordinate clauses of which those
that follow begin with <xex>nor</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fight <qex>neither</qex> with small nor great, save only with the
king.</q> <rj><qau>1 Kings xxii. 31.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hadst thou been firm and fixed in thy dissent,⟦br⟧
<qex>Neither</qex> had I transgressed, nor thou with me.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When she put it on, she made me vow⟦br⟧
That I should <qex>neither</qex> sell, nor give, nor lose it.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Neither</xex> was formerly often used where we now
use <xex>nor</xex>. ⟦ldquo⟧For neither circumcision, <xex>neither</xex>
uncircumcision is anything at all.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Tyndale.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧Ye
shall not eat of it, <xex>neither</xex> shall ye touch it.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Gen. iii. 3.</au> <xex>Neither</xex> is sometimes used colloquially
at the end of a clause to enforce a foregoing negative (<xex>nor</xex>,
<xex>not</xex>, <xex>no</xex>). ⟦ldquo⟧He is very tall, but not too tall
<xex>neither</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Addison.</au> ⟦rdquo⟧ ⟦lsquo⟧I care not
for his thrust' ⟦lsquo⟧No, nor I <xex>neither</xex>.'⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Shak.</au></note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Not so neither</b></col>, <cd>by no means.</cd>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>nekton</ent>⟦br⟧
